GRANTS — NO LICENCE FEE REQUIRED

The following uses are permitted without a commercial licence agreement:

1. Individual Use
   Any natural person may use, study, modify, and build upon the Software
   for personal, educational, or non-commercial purposes.

2. Non-Commercial Organisations
   Non-profit organisations, universities, schools, and government research
   bodies may use and modify the Software for internal and research purposes.

3. Small Businesses
   Legal entities qualifying as a Small Business under the definition above
   may use the Software internally and incorporate it into products or
   services, provided annual revenue remains below the threshold.
   Once annual revenue exceeds USD $1,000,000 you must obtain a commercial
   licence within 90 days.

4. Open Source Projects
   You may use, modify, and redistribute the Software or derivative works
   as part of a project whose complete source code is published under an
   approved open source licence (OSI-approved), provided you include
   attribution as described below.

5. Security Research & CTF
   Security researchers, penetration testers, and CTF participants may use
   the Software for authorised security testing, research, and competitions.

---

CONDITIONS THAT APPLY TO ALL FREE USES

A. Attribution
   Any distribution, product, publication, or public demonstration that
   incorporates the Software or is derived from it must include:
     - The text "Powered by RogueOS" or "Built on RogueOS" in a visible
       location (documentation, about screen, or equivalent), and
     - A link to the project repository or the author's contact.

B. Notices
   You may not remove or alter any copyright, licence, or attribution notices
   present in the Software.

C. No Misrepresentation
   You may not represent the Software as your own original work, claim
   authorship of the core OS, or imply endorsement by the author.

D. Sharing Modifications (Open Source use only)
   If you redistribute the Software under clause 4 (Open Source Projects),
   your modifications must be made available under the same or a compatible
   open source licence.

